### Configuration Files

#### addons.yaml

Defines which addon repos to include. Each repo can be either a simple list of modules or an object with `revision` and `modules` keys:

```yaml
ENV:
  DEFAULT_REPO_PATTERN: "{{ default_repo_pattern }}"
  ODOO_VERSION: "{{ odoo_version }}"

# Simple format — tracks the branch from ENV.ODOO_VERSION:
queue:
  - "queue_job"
  - "queue_job_cron"

# Object format — pins to a specific commit (full 40-char SHA required):
connector:
  revision: abc123abc123abc123abc123abc123abc123abc1
  modules:
    - "component"
    - "connector"
# ...
```

When `revision` is specified, only that single commit is fetched (`git fetch --depth 1 origin <hash>`), keeping the checkout as lightweight as a shallow clone.

#### repos.yaml

Defines Odoo source repository. Supports an optional `revision` field to pin to a specific commit:

```yaml
./src/odoo:
  remotes:
    github: https://github.com/odoo/odoo.git
  target: github {{ odoo_version }}
  revision: fb06021aa0e3cf4b9d41e64f4b0874577f1b4ad8  # optional — full 40-char SHA required
```

When `revision` is specified, only that single commit is fetched (`git fetch --depth 1 origin <hash>`), keeping the checkout as lightweight as a shallow clone. **Must be a full 40-character commit SHA** — short hashes are not supported by `git fetch`.

#### pyproject.toml / uv.lock

Python dependencies are imported straight from Odoo's own `requirements.txt`:

```bash
nix run .#bootstrap-deps   # after update-repos; runs `uv add -r src/odoo/requirements.txt` + `uv lock`
```

### How To Update Server

To update the server with the latest code and addons, run:

```bash
cd ${{ project_dir_var }}
git pull
nix run .#update-repos
odoo -c ${{ project_dir_var }}/odoo.conf -u module_name --workers 0 --stop-after-init --logfile=/dev/stdout
systemctl --user restart odoo.service
```

## Local Server

### Quick Setup For Development

This will:

1. Create `.env` file with configuration
1. Clone/update all repositories
1. Generate Odoo configuration
1. Initialize PostgreSQL database
{% if prod_ssh_host %}
1. Setup SSH access for servers
{% endif %}
{% if backup_s3_bucket %}
1. Configure AWS credentials
{% endif %}
1. Create Nginx configuration
{% if editor == 'vscode' %}
1. Create VSCode settings
{% endif %}

```bash
cd {{ project_name }}

# Run full setup
nix run .#setup-dev

# Lock python dependencies from src/odoo/requirements.txt
nix run .#bootstrap-deps

# INSTALL PERMANENTLY TO YOUR SYSTEM
nix profile add .#dev-server

# Odoo, Postgres and Nginx services + log rotation
systemctl --user enable odoo.service postgres.service nginx.service odoo-logrotate.timer
systemctl --user start odoo.service postgres.service nginx.service odoo-logrotate.timer
systemctl --user restart odoo.service postgres.service nginx.service
systemctl --user stop odoo.service postgres.service nginx.service
systemctl --user status odoo.service postgres.service nginx.service

# Logs:
tail -f ${{ project_dir_var }}/.postgres/log/postgresql.log | ccze -A
journalctl --user -u odoo.service -f | ccze -A
tail -f ${{ project_dir_var }}/odoo.log | ccze -A
journalctl --user -u nginx.service -f | ccze -A

# Odoo update module:
odoo -c ${{ project_dir_var }}/odoo.conf -u module_name --workers 0 --stop-after-init --logfile=/dev/stdout

# Odoo shell:
odoo shell -c ${{ project_dir_var }}/odoo.conf --workers 0 --stop-after-init
{% if prod_ssh_host %}

# Connect to remote servers:
{% if test_ssh_host %}
test-server
{% endif %}
prod-server
{% endif %}
{% if backup_s3_bucket %}

# Download and restore production backup with name from .env file
nix run .#download-backup
# Or with custom database name:
nix run .#download-backup -- dbname
# Or skip download and use existing backup:
nix run .#download-backup -- dbname --skip-download
{% endif %}

# help message with all commands and URLs:
welcome-message
```

